<message><from> ac.uk </from><to> ac.uk </to><subject><text_normal> ^ reminder : linguistic society talk this thursday </text_normal></subject><date> 25 feb 2003 15:16:47 +0000 </date><content-type> text/plain; format=flowed; charset=iso-8859-1 </content-type><message_body><text_normal> ^ the  ame university linguistic society will meet on thursday  um  ame ,  um : ^ dr  ame  ame  ame  ame  ame  ame for english and  ame  ame , university of  ame ^ will talk on ^ "  ame production by language learners " ( abstract below ) ^  ame : thursday  um  ame , 5.00pm ( tea served from 4.30pm )  ame : the  ame library ,  ame college ,  ame street . ^ following the talk , the society 's officers will take the speaker out to dinner at a local restaurant ; members of the audience are most welcome to join us . ^ membership of the society for  um remains at  um pounds (  um pounds for students ) . ^ if not already paid , subscriptions can be brought to the meeting . ^ cheques should be made payable to  ame university linguistic society . ^ agreement production by language learners ^ many domains of language processing ( e.g. , syntactic ambiguity resolution , anaphor resolution , phrase order selection ) require the co-ordination / integration of syntactic and non-syntactic information . ^ in recent years , studies have begun to emerge which use standard experimental psycholinguistic and neurolinguistic research methodologies to investigate how native-like bilinguals and proficient second language ( l2 ) users " syntactic and non-syntactic processes in sentence comprehension are . ^ the present study aims to extend this line of enquiry to subject-verb agreement in sentence production , another domain of language processing that has been argued to involve the integration of syntactic and non-syntactic ( e.g. , semantic / conceptual ) information . ^ it examines whether proficient l2 english speakers show native-like sensitivity to syntactic and semantic / conceptual information in agreement implementation . ^ this paper will begin with reviews of  um areas of research , the recent l2 processing literature which suggests that l2 users tend to have native-like non-syntactic processes but non-native-like syntactic processes in sentence comprehension and the ( l1 ) language production literature which demonstrates l1 speakers " sensitivity to syntactic and semantic / conceptual information in agreement implementation . ^  um parallel experiments will then be presented which were designed to probe whether proficient spanish and chinese l2 english speakers make use of syntactic and semantic / conceptual information in agreement production in their l2 . ^ the results will then be used to address general questions about the development of l2 processing routines . </text_normal></message_body></message>